      <h2 class='section-heading-centered'>HAP's Rules for Working with AI</h2>
      <p class='mb-2'>After creating quote-hap.json with AI assistance, I've developed six non-negotiable rules. These aren't suggestions‚Äîthey're requirements that Prof. Teeters validated. Follow them every time you use AI for coding tasks.</p>

      <div class='tip-card'>
        <div class='tip-number'>1</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Always Specify Schema Requirements First</h3>
          <p>AI doesn't know your project's rules unless you provide them. Start EVERY prompt by pasting your schema or listing required fields. Don't assume AI remembers context from earlier. Schema compliance isn't optional‚Äîit's foundational. Without it, AI generates plausible-looking code that fails validation every time.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class='tip-card'>
        <div class='tip-number'>2</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Detailed Prompts Get Professional Results</h3>
          <p>"Generate quotes" produces junk. "Generate 5 reflective developer-wisdom quotes, 10-20 words each, category 'developer-wisdom', following exact schema with fields id/category/tone/text/source, focused on computational thinking concepts from Stations 1-5" produces quality. The length of your prompt correlates directly with the quality of AI output.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class='tip-card'>
        <div class='tip-number'>3</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Verify Everything Before Committing</h3>
          <p>Run <code>npm run validate</code> before Git operations. Test manually even if validation passes. Read the output‚Äîdon't just trust that it looks right. If you can't explain what the code does or why it's correct, you don't own it yet. Verification catches AI hallucinations, schema violations, and logical errors that look syntactically perfect.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class='tip-card'>
        <div class='tip-number'>4</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Understanding Beats Speed</h3>
          <p>AI can generate code faster than you can type, but speed without comprehension is technical debt. Read every line AI produces. Understand WHY it made each choice. Learn from the patterns. If Prof. Teeters asked you to explain this code, could you? If not, slow down and study it before accepting it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class='tip-card'>
        <div class='tip-number'>5</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Quality Requires Explicit Constraints</h3>
          <p>AI won't optimize quality unless you define it. Include quality constraints in prompts: "concise" (10-20 words), "specific" (reference actual practices), "actionable" (something learners can do), "plain language" (no jargon). Generic prompts produce generic output. Professional prompts produce professional code.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class='tip-card'>
        <div class='tip-number'>6</div>
        <div>
          <h3>You Own Every Line of Code</h3>
          <p>Whether you typed it or AI generated it, you're responsible for quality, correctness, and schema compliance. Blame doesn't transfer to the AI when validation fails. Your name goes on the commit message. Own the code by verifying it, understanding it, and being willing to explain every decision it represents.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

