      <h2>When NOT to Use AI</h2>
      <p class='mb-2'>AI is powerful for generating code, but it's not always the right tool. Understanding when to work manually is just as important as knowing when to use AI. Prof. Teeters taught me these three scenarios where manual work beats AI speed.</p>

      <div class='analysis-grid mt-2'>
        <div class='analysis-point'>
          <h3>When You're Learning New Concepts</h3>
          <p><strong>Manual work builds understanding.</strong> If this is your first time working with JSON schemas, Git workflows, or project structures, type the code yourself. AI generates correct output but skips the learning process. You learn by doing, by making mistakes, by debugging your own errors. Use AI after you understand the fundamentals, not before.</p>
        </div>

        <div class='analysis-point'>
          <h3>When the Task Requires Judgment</h3>
          <p><strong>AI can't make quality decisions for you.</strong> Choosing WHICH computational thinking lessons matter most, WHICH quotes represent your learning journey, WHICH tone fits your voice‚Äîthese are judgment calls. AI generates plausible options, but you decide what's good. Don't outsource the thinking that makes your work meaningful.</p>
        </div>

        <div class='analysis-point'>
          <h3>When Verification Takes Longer Than Writing</h3>
          <p><strong>Sometimes manual is faster.</strong> For simple tasks (creating one quote, fixing a typo, adjusting a field), typing it yourself takes 30 seconds. Crafting a detailed AI prompt, reviewing output, and verifying correctness takes 2 minutes. Use AI for repetitive tasks (generating 10 similar quotes), not one-off edits.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

